        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "[codex] add iOS mobile app",
        "body": "## Summary\n\nAdds a new `mobile/` Expo app for Crabbox with an iOS-first native shell around `crabbox.sh` and self-hosted Crabbox coordinators.\n\n## What changed\n\n- Scaffolds an Expo SDK 56 TypeScript app under `mobile/`.\n- Builds a native WebView client that preserves portal/GitHub OAuth cookies, supports iOS back gestures and pull-to-refresh, and exposes native back, home, reload, share, open-in-browser, and coordinator settings controls.\n- Persists a configurable coordinator URL, defaulting to `https://crabbox.sh`.\n- Requires HTTPS coordinator sessions by default; development builds allow only loopback HTTP URLs and the WebView no longer whitelists arbitrary cleartext origins.\n- Adds branded Crabbox icon/splash assets generated from a tracked SVG source.\n- Adds a `Mobile` CI job for install, coordinator URL policy tests, TypeScript, and iOS bundle export.\n- Documents Mac/iOS run steps, Xcode setup, Expo dev menu usage, coordinator URL policy, and native prebuild flow.\n\n## User impact\n\nThis gives Crabbox a concrete first mobile app surface focused on iOS. Users can launch the Crabbox web portal in a native container, stay signed in through WebView cookies, and switch to a team/self-hosted broker without changing code.\n\n## Validation\n\n- `npm ci` from `mobile/`\n- `npm run test:urls` from `mobile/`\n- `npm run check` from `mobile/`\n- `npx expo export --platform ios --output-dir /tmp/crabbox-mobile-export` from `mobile/`\n- `git diff --check`\n- GitHub Actions CI run https://github.com/openclaw/crabbox/actions/runs/27529710307: `Go`, `Apple VZ`, `Worker`, `Mobile`, `Scripts`, `Docs`, and `Release Check` all passed.\n- `npm audit --omit=dev` reports a moderate transitive `uuid` advisory through Expo CLI/config tooling; npm's forced fix would move Expo to an incompatible old Expo version, so the SDK-compatible lockfile is left unchanged.\n\n## Local iOS note\n\nI could not launch the simulator on this machine because `xcode-select -p` points to `/Library/Developer/CommandLineTools`, `xcrun simctl` is unavailable, and there is no `/Applications/Xcode*.app`. The README includes the Xcode selection commands needed before `npm run ios` can open the simulator. Real login-persistence and coordinator-switching proof still needs a Mac with full Xcode plus a redacted test session or device/simulator capture.",
